<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Ambassador in China (
                        Stuart
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1949v08</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d1</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">1</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1949-01-03T02:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1949-01-03T02:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-01-03T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-01-03T02:00:00-05:00" n="1" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–349: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-01-03T15:00:00+08:00">January 3, 1949—3 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:39 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5. Although press is playing up Generalissimo’s<note n="2" xml:id="d1fn2">Chiang
                        Kai-shek, President of the Republic of China.</note> New Year’s
                        statement<note n="3" xml:id="d1fn3">Department of State, <hi rend="italic">United States Relations With China</hi> (Washington, Government
                        Printing Office, 1949), p. 920.</note> as indication his willingness step
                    aside to permit peace, Lu Han, Governor Yunnan, who attended military
                    discussions informs us intention Generalissimo’s statement is “if Communists
                    want peace they can have peace; if they want war they can have war”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
